text: ¬†@cheriyuna¬†come on, there is a difference between handmade fresh pasta and main stream brands of industrially processed dried pasta, some brands even sell with different ingredients in US compared to EU. If you make pasta by hand from high semolina wheat flour as is traditional in Italy, it has much higher protein content and is much less processed. Even most good quality dried pasta brands in Italy will be focusing on traditional process and high quality ingredients to make their pasta in the most simple way possible. If you can find them, I recommend Rummo, Voiello, La Molisana, Garofalo, it really makes difference to have high quality pasta in such a simple dish as Carbonara.

text: ¬†@hisdud3ness93¬† i‚Äôm not saying there isn‚Äôt a clear difference, it‚Äôs just that it‚Äôs still processed food either way
author: @cheriyuna

text: ¬†@cheriyuna¬† you can argue anything that is cooked, chopped, or altered in any way from it‚Äôs natural state is processed, but it is universally understood that what most people mean by processed foods are industrially processed products with artificial ingredients and additives.
author: @hisdud3ness93

text: ¬†@hisdud3ness93¬† .. yeah? point still stands, though - people often mistake healthier foods for being unprocessed, and i would say it‚Äôs better to play safe & not spread misinformation, just in case others who are unaware come across these comments - because even if it is ‚Äúuniversally understood‚Äù, there will always be people that do not know, especially if one is not fluent in english

text: ¬†@toffonardi7037¬†, I‚Äôm not saying there are photos of the food like people take today, but there are multiple photos of first two restaurants in Roma that served Carbonara. In those photos, you can clearly see them advertising on chalkboards outside of the restaurants and on chalkboard menus ‚Äúspaghetti con guanciale e uovo‚Äù and ‚Äúspaghetti con pancetta e uovo‚Äù. Over time, the version with guanciale became preferred. The Ministry of Culture, Ministry of Agriculture and Food Sovereignty, the State Archive of Roma, and the Accademia Italiana della Cucina all maintain similar photos along with photos of old recipes. The reason that it became known as ‚Äúspaghetti all Carbonara‚Äù is because of the two restaurants called ‚ÄúLa Carbonara‚Äù that popularized the dishes. One opened in 1907 and the other one around 1915.
author: @geoffreyk9164

text: ¬†@toffonardi7037¬†, False. As I have clearly stated from the beginning both guanciale and pancetta were used. It is almost certainly based on what was simply available each day. There is significant archived information with information about the original Cafbonaras from the early 1900‚Äôs. From the history, it would seem that guanciale became preferred by at least the 1960‚Äôs. I have evaluated many restaurants in Roma and have the original recipe from one of the most famous Carbonaras that the family claims to have used since at least the 1960‚Äôs and it clearly calls for guanciale.

text: ¬†@geoffreyk9164¬† I mean exactly the "slight variations" and "subtle differences" you talk about. There is no absolute originality in recipes, music, art or any form of human expression in general. I cannot stand people that claim their version or perception of things is the "real and original one" and all the different ones are "wrong". Let alone when we talk about a dish of bloody pasta...
author: @grgr6720

text: ¬†@grgr6720¬†, Well, there is a base recipe like there is for say a Negroni. You can tweak things like blending different vermouths or adjusting ratios slightly and it‚Äôs still Negroni, but the second you swap the gin for bourbon or mezcal, you‚Äôre making a completely different drink. Most certainly there was an original and sometimes there‚Äôs a widely excepted modern variation, but in general, you should only be changing measures and blending if you want to stay within the confines of an original or widely accepted recipe.
